When a small longitudinal compression force is applied to the ends of a rod, the rod merely becomes slightly shorter. But if the force is large enough, the rod responds by buckling radially outwards. Early on in the development of the theory of elasticity, Euler found that buckling of a rod of given length L and elastic bending stiffness B is a critical phenomenon,
FEuler 1⁄4 4p2 B
